# Rule 08 — Product-Docs Maintenance (alwaysApply)

This rule is the operational companion to [ADR-005](../../docs/adr/005-product-direction-framework.md).
ADR-005 is authoritative for intent; this rule is authoritative for
enforcement behavior. In any conflict, ADR-005 wins.

## Precedence

This rule operates under `.cursor/rules/00-global-architecture.mdc`
§Precedence. It does not override AGENTS.md, the architecture
charter, or ADR-005; it enforces them.

---

## 1. Closed set of product docs

`docs/product/` contains exactly these files:

- `00-vision.md` — mission, niches, locked strategic decisions, claim ledger
- `01-competitive-landscape.md` — per-niche competitor map
- `02-roadmap.md` — phase definitions, entry/exit criteria, non-goals
- `03-definition-of-done.md` — per-phase exit bar, workflow benchmarks
- `04-compliance-and-legal.md` — compliance maturity, regulatory scope
- `05-interop-and-reference-data.md` — FHIR/US Core/SMART surface, licensing
- `06-ux-and-workflow.md` — workflow principles, design-system, accessibility

Adding a seventh file is **prohibited** without a superseding ADR. If
an agent believes new product content belongs somewhere other than one
of these six, it MUST halt and request human direction rather than
create a new file.

---

## 2. Frontmatter requirement

Every file in `docs/product/` MUST carry, at the top of the file,
frontmatter of this exact shape:

```yaml
---
status: Draft | Active | Under Review | Superseded
last_reviewed: YYYY-MM-DD
next_review: YYYY-MM-DD
cadence: stable-yearly | quarterly | living-per-slice | event-driven
owner: <name>
---
```

An agent editing a `docs/product/` file MUST update `last_reviewed`
when content changes meaningfully, and MUST update `next_review` to
a date consistent with the file's cadence.

---

## 3. Tier classification for docs/product/

`docs/product/**` is **Tier 2 by default**.

A change **escalates to Tier 3** if and only if its diff materially
alters ANY of the following content categories:

| Category | File & section |
| ---- | ---- |
| Roadmap phase definitions (entry, exit, order, non-goals, set of phases) | `02-roadmap.md` — phase rows |
| Claim ledger | `00-vision.md` — `## Claim Ledger` section |
| Compliance posture statements moving between "claimed" and "not claimed" | `04-compliance-and-legal.md` — §Claim Ledger Reconciliation |
| Compliance maturity phase boundaries (A/B/C/D) | `04-compliance-and-legal.md` — §Maturity Phases |
| Regulatory scope declarations (HIPAA, state privacy, SaMD boundary, ONC track) | `04-compliance-and-legal.md` |
| Definition-of-Done thresholds (workflow benchmarks, gate conditions) | `03-definition-of-done.md` |
| Reference-data licensing stance (e.g., deciding to license CPT) | `05-interop-and-reference-data.md` — §Reference Data |

Non-escalating edits (Tier 2) include: typo fixes; clarifying prose;
cadence-driven review refreshes that re-affirm existing content;
adding a competitor row to `01-competitive-landscape.md`; updating
`last_reviewed` / `next_review` frontmatter; renaming a section
header without changing content; restructuring paragraphs without
changing positions declared above.

**Classification tie-breaker (inherited from ADR-004 §2.1):** when
a change's tier is ambiguous, Tier 3. Agents MUST NOT classify down
in the face of doubt.

**Mixed-slice rule:** if a slice includes any non-`docs/product/`
change that is itself Tier 2 or Tier 3, the highest-tier-touched
rule from ADR-004 applies.

---

## 4. Roadmap-Phase trailer (universal precondition)

Every code-bearing commit (i.e., any commit that touches files
outside `docs/project-timeline.md`) MUST include, in its body,
exactly one `Roadmap-Phase:` trailer of the form:

```
Roadmap-Phase: <phase> (<short description>)
```

Rules:

- **Exactly one** trailer. Lists, ranges, and multi-phase
  classifications are prohibited.
- The `<phase>` value MUST be one of:
  - A phase identifier present as a row in `docs/product/02-roadmap.md`
    (e.g., `3F`, `4A`, `5D`).
  - The literal token `governance` (ADRs, rules, `AGENTS.md`
    amendments, charter amendments, product-framework docs).
  - The literal token `docs` (updates to `docs/project-timeline.md`
    only).
- For commits under the `governance` token: the commit body MUST
  cite which ADR, rule, or governance file the slice advances.

**Reserved scope of the `governance` token (ADR-005 §2.5).** The
`governance` token is permitted ONLY for commits whose diff is
wholly contained within:

- `docs/adr/**`
- `AGENTS.md`
- `.cursor/rules/**`
- `.claude/**`
- `docs/architecture/**`
- `docs/product/**`

A commit that also touches feature code, platform code, database
migrations, infrastructure, or any other non-governance path MUST
use a roadmap-phase identifier. Using `governance` to label
feature, platform, or bug-fix work is a governance incident and
halts the commit under ADR-004 §2.3 guardrail 7.

**Reserved scope of the `docs` token.** The `docs` token is
permitted ONLY for commits whose diff is wholly contained within
`docs/project-timeline.md`. Any commit that also touches code,
migrations, or governance files MUST use a roadmap-phase
identifier or `governance`, not `docs`.

Commits that predate ADR-005's landing are exempt from this rule.
No retroactive rewriting is required or permitted.

---

## 5. Living-doc review cadence

Every file in `docs/product/` carries a `next_review:` date. On the
first slice after a `next_review:` date has passed, the agent MUST
either:

1. **Refresh the doc** — review its content, update or re-affirm as
   needed, bump `last_reviewed:` to today, and set `next_review:` to
   a new date consistent with the cadence. The refresh may be its
   own slice (typically Tier 2) or may ride alongside a larger slice
   that already touches the doc.

2. **Defer the review** — add a `Review-Deferred:` line to the
   commit body naming the specific date the review is deferred to
   (MUST be within 30 days of the original `next_review:` date) and
   the reason. Add a carry-forward item to the commit body tracking
   the deferral. Repeated deferrals on the same doc across more than
   two slices MUST halt and flag for human input.

---

## 6. Docs-must-not-block-commits

If a code-bearing slice requires a `docs/product/**` update per §3
but the exact change is unclear, ambiguous, or would demand
product decisions the agent cannot confidently make, the agent
MUST:

1. Insert a `TODO(review)` marker in the affected doc section,
   naming the specific question. Example:

   ```markdown
   <!-- TODO(review): does phase 4C exit criterion need adjustment
        given the document-storage deferral? Flagged in commit <sha>. -->
   ```

2. Cite the marker in the commit body under a `Docs-Review-TODO:`
   trailer. Example:

   ```
   Docs-Review-TODO: docs/product/02-roadmap.md §Phase 4C —
   question about exit criterion adjustment for document-storage
   deferral. Follow-up slice required.
   ```

3. Add the marker resolution to carry-forward.

**Required conditions for `TODO(review)` use (ADR-005 §2.4).**
A `TODO(review)` marker is permitted ONLY when BOTH:

- **(a)** the doc-update change impact is genuinely ambiguous (the
  agent cannot confidently decide what the doc should say), AND
- **(b)** the commit body contains a matching `Docs-Review-TODO:`
  trailer naming the specific file, section, and question.

Inserting a `TODO(review)` marker without the trailer, or using
the trailer without inserting the marker, is a governance
incident and halts the commit under ADR-004 §2.3 guardrail 3.

**Hard cap on active markers.** No more than **3 active
`TODO(review)` markers per `docs/product/**` file** at any time.
An "active" marker is any unresolved `TODO(review)` comment in
the file; resolution requires both removing the marker and
answering the underlying question (content written, or question
declared moot with a one-line rationale in the slice that removes
the marker).

A slice that would push any `docs/product/**` file to a 4th active
marker MUST halt under ADR-004 §2.3 and EITHER:

- Resolve an existing marker in the same slice to stay at or below
  the cap, OR
- Re-scope to avoid adding a new marker, OR
- Flag for human input with a stop-and-flag report naming the
  outstanding markers and proposing a resolution path.

**Visibility requirement.** Every slice's pre-commit review pack
that touches a `docs/product/**` file MUST report the
active-`TODO(review)`-count for that file both before and after
the slice. This makes the cap visible to the human reviewer at
approval time.

This escape hatch exists so documentation ambiguity never blocks
forward code progress. The cap, the required marker/trailer
pairing, and the visible count are the guardrails that prevent it
from becoming a silent-decay vector. Repeated use on the same doc
across more than two slices without resolution MUST halt and flag
for human input.

---

## 7. Pre-commit checklist (agent self-verification)

Before any commit that touches, OR is logically connected to, a
`docs/product/` file, the agent MUST verify in the review pack:

- [ ] The slice's tier classification considered the §3 escalation
      triggers. Any escalation is declared in the commit body.
- [ ] Every modified `docs/product/` file has its `last_reviewed:`
      bumped (unless the change is frontmatter-only or pure typo fix).
- [ ] Every modified `docs/product/` file has a `next_review:`
      consistent with its cadence.
- [ ] The `Roadmap-Phase:` trailer is present and matches a roadmap
      row or is `governance` / `docs`.
- [ ] If a `docs/product/` update was required by §3 but not made,
      a `TODO(review)` marker and a `Docs-Review-TODO:` commit-body
      line are present per §6.
- [ ] If any `docs/product/` file's `next_review:` has passed, §5 is
      satisfied (refreshed OR a `Review-Deferred:` line is present).
- [ ] For every `docs/product/**` file touched by the slice, the
      active-`TODO(review)`-count is reported before and after the
      slice, and no file exceeds **3 active markers** post-slice
      (§6 hard cap).
- [ ] Every `TODO(review)` marker inserted by the slice has a
      matching `Docs-Review-TODO:` trailer in the commit body (§6
      required pairing).
- [ ] If the commit uses `Roadmap-Phase: governance` or
      `Roadmap-Phase: docs`, the reserved-scope constraints in §4
      are satisfied (diff wholly contained within the reserved
      paths).

Failure to satisfy any item halts the commit per ADR-004 §2.3
universal guardrails.

---

## 8. Enforcement

- **Agent-level:** this rule is `alwaysApply: true` for the file
  globs above; Cursor loads it into every session's context. Agents
  MUST treat violations as stop-and-flag events.
- **Human-level:** the repository owner validates the §7 checklist
  in every review pack that touches product docs OR that advances
  a roadmap phase.
- **CI-level:** deferred to Phase 3I. At that point a CI check will
  mechanically enforce §§4, 5, 6, and 7. Until then, agent + human
  enforcement is the operative control.

---

## 9. Relationship to ADR-004

This rule does not modify ADR-004. It extends ADR-004's tier model
to the new `docs/product/` directory with a content-based
classification rule. The universal preconditions and guardrails
from AGENTS.md §§4.7.3 and 4.7.4 apply to every slice this rule
governs. Override phrases from AGENTS.md §4.7.2 supersede tier
autonomy as normal.

---

## 10. Amendment

This rule is amended only by a superseding or amending ADR. Direct
edits to this file's enforcement semantics without an ADR are
prohibited. Typo fixes and prose clarifications that do not change
enforcement behavior are permitted as Tier 3 governance edits per
AGENTS.md §4.7.1.
